# Should Schools Focus on Teens' Health? An In-Depth Analysis

The health of teenagers is a critical concern globally, given the significant physical, emotional, and psychological changes they undergo during adolescence. Schools, as primary environments for youth development, have a unique opportunity and responsibility to influence teens' health positively. This report analyzes whether schools should focus on teens' health, drawing on recent and reliable research and data. It considers physical health, mental health, preventive care, and the role of school-based programs, ultimately providing an evidence-based conclusion.

---

## Importance of Focusing on Teens' Health in Schools

### Physical Health and Physical Education

Physical activity is essential for adolescents' healthy development. The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services recommends that youth aged 6â€“17 engage in at least 60 minutes of daily physical activity to build healthy bones, improve strength, reduce obesity risk, and promote psychological well-being ([Wagner, n.d.](https://www.hertzfurniture.com/buying-guide/healthy-environment/physical-education-benefits.html)).

However, data indicate a decline in physical education (PE) participation among teens. For example, only 24% of grade 12 students attend PE classes, down from 41% in grade 9 ([Wagner, n.d.](https://www.hertzfurniture.com/buying-guide/healthy-environment/physical-education-benefits.html)). This trend is concerning given the rise in adolescent obesity and related health issues such as cardiovascular disease and diabetes.

Mandatory PE in schools has several documented benefits:

| **Advantages of Mandatory PE**                          | **Supporting Evidence**                                                                                  |
|--------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Promotes healthy habits and combats lifestyle diseases | Regular physical activity reduces risks of obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease ([Anderson, n.d.](https://www.theclassroom.com/advantages-disadvantages-mandatory-pe-schools-12271285.html)) |
| Improves academic performance                           | Studies show a correlation between physical fitness and better grades, concentration, and behavior ([Wagner, n.d.](https://www.hertzfurniture.com/buying-guide/healthy-environment/physical-education-benefits.html)) |
| Builds character and social skills                      | PE fosters responsibility, teamwork, and discipline ([Prosancons, 2018](https://prosancons.com/education/pros-and-cons-of-physical-education/)) |
| Motivates school attendance                             | PE can be a primary motivator for some students to attend school ([Prosancons, 2018](https://prosancons.com/education/pros-and-cons-of-physical-education/)) |

Despite these benefits, some studies reveal that gym classes often involve limited actual physical activity (only about 16 minutes of a 45-minute class), and some students experience anxiety or decreased self-confidence due to performance-based grading ([Junior Scholastic, 2020](https://junior.scholastic.com/issues/2019-20/032320/should-teens-have-to-take-gym-every-day.html)). Thus, while PE is beneficial, its implementation requires careful design to maximize engagement and inclusivity.

### Mental Health and School Environment

Adolescent mental health is a growing concern. One in five teens experiences mental health issues, which can lead to risky behaviors such as substance abuse, violence, and poor academic outcomes ([CDC, n.d.](https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/healthservices/index.htm); [Lagosmums, 2019](https://lagosmums.com/why-your-teenagers-health-is-important/)).

Schools can play a pivotal role in promoting positive mental health through comprehensive, long-term interventions. Systematic reviews indicate that school-wide programs focusing on positive mental health promotion, social and emotional learning, mindfulness, and mental health literacy are effective, especially when sustained over a year or longer ([Clarke et al., 2021](https://www.eif.org.uk/report/adolescent-mental-health-a-systematic-review-on-the-effectiveness-of-school-based-interventions)).

Moreover, the psychosocial climate of schools significantly affects adolescent mental health and wellbeing. Positive relationships with peers and adults, a sense of safety, and student involvement in decision-making contribute to better health, behavior, and academic outcomes ([Kutsyuruba et al., 2015](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0883035517313794)).

| **Key School Climate Factors Impacting Mental Health** | **Impact on Adolescents**                                                                                   |
|--------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Positive relationships with peers and adults           | Improve health, academic, and behavioral outcomes                                                           |
| Perceived school safety                                 | Reduces antisocial behavior and promotes engagement                                                         |
| Student involvement in decision-making                 | Enhances school connectedness and wellbeing                                                                 |
| Comprehensive mental health programs                    | Promote positive mental health and prevent difficulties                                                      |

Schools are uniquely positioned to provide mental health services or referrals, fostering environments that support emotional wellbeing and resilience ([CDC, n.d.](https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/healthservices/index.htm)).

### Preventive Health Services and Access

Adolescents often underutilize preventive health services, including vaccinations, screenings, and sexual health services, despite official guidelines recommending these ([CDC, n.d.](https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/healthservices/index.htm)). Schools can bridge this gap by offering on-site services or facilitating referrals to youth-friendly providers.

Preventive care is critical to early identification of health issues and reducing long-term risks. For example, teens are disproportionately affected by HIV and sexually transmitted diseases, yet testing rates remain low ([CDC, n.d.](https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/healthservices/index.htm)).

Schools can normalize preventive care by integrating health education and services, thereby improving community health outcomes and reducing disparities, especially for disadvantaged youth ([Atkins et al., 2017](https://ukdiss.com/examples/adolescent-development-social-impacts.php)).

