## Challenges and Considerations

While the benefits of focusing on teens' health in schools are clear, several challenges must be acknowledged:

| **Challenges**                                         | **Details**                                                                                                    |
|-------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Limited time and resources                             | Schools face pressure to prioritize academic subjects, sometimes reducing time for PE and health programs ([Junior Scholastic, 2020](https://junior.scholastic.com/issues/2019-20/032320/should-teens-have-to-take-gym-every-day.html)) |
| Varied student needs and inclusivity                  | Disabled students or those with non-sporting talents may feel disadvantaged in PE programs ([Prosancons, 2018](https://prosancons.com/education/pros-and-cons-of-physical-education/)) |
| Risk of injury and anxiety                             | Physical activities carry injury risks; some students experience anxiety or lowered self-esteem in PE ([Junior Scholastic, 2020](https://junior.scholastic.com/issues/2019-20/032320/should-teens-have-to-take-gym-every-day.html)) |
| Financial costs                                       | Additional costs for sports gear and activity fees may burden students and families ([Prosancons, 2018](https://prosancons.com/education/pros-and-cons-of-physical-education/)) |
| Implementation quality                                | Simply increasing PE time without improving program quality may not yield health benefits ([Public School Review, n.d.](https://www.publicschoolreview.com/blog/the-pros-and-cons-of-mandatory-gym-class-in-public-schools)) |

Addressing these challenges requires thoughtful program design, adequate funding, teacher training, and inclusive policies that accommodate diverse student needs.

---

## Recommendations for Schools

To maximize the benefits of focusing on teens' health, schools should adopt a holistic and evidence-based approach:

1. **Integrate Physical and Mental Health Programs:** Combine PE with mental health promotion, social-emotional learning, and mindfulness to support overall wellbeing ([Clarke et al., 2021](https://www.eif.org.uk/report/adolescent-mental-health-a-systematic-review-on-the-effectiveness-of-school-based-interventions)).

2. **Ensure Quality and Inclusivity in PE:** Design PE curricula that engage all students, including those with disabilities or non-athletic interests, and avoid performance-based grading that harms self-esteem ([Junior Scholastic, 2020](https://junior.scholastic.com/issues/2019-20/032320/should-teens-have-to-take-gym-every-day.html)).

3. **Provide Preventive Health Services On-Site:** Expand school-based health centers and collaborate with community providers to offer vaccinations, screenings, and sexual health services ([CDC, n.d.](https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/healthservices/index.htm)).

4. **Create a Positive School Climate:** Foster safe, supportive environments with strong relationships and student participation in decision-making ([Kutsyuruba et al., 2015](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0883035517313794)).

5. **Educate on Nutrition and Healthy Habits:** While nutrition education is complex, schools should provide basic guidance to help students make informed choices, considering diverse dietary needs ([Debate.org, n.d.](https://www.debate.org/opinions/should-nutrition-be-a-mandatory-part-of-education)).

6. **Monitor and Evaluate Programs:** Use data to assess the effectiveness of health initiatives and adjust strategies accordingly ([Clarke et al., 2021](https://www.eif.org.uk/report/adolescent-mental-health-a-systematic-review-on-the-effectiveness-of-school-based-interventions)).

---

## Conclusion

The evidence strongly supports that schools should focus on teens' health as a fundamental component of education. Physical education, mental health promotion, preventive services, and a positive school climate collectively contribute to healthier, more engaged, and academically successful adolescents. While challenges exist, they are surmountable with intentional, inclusive, and well-resourced strategies.

Given the rising rates of obesity, mental health issues, and risky behaviors among teens, schools have both an opportunity and an obligation to act. Prioritizing teen health within schools not only benefits individual students but also has long-term societal advantages by fostering healthier adult populations.

